segments.text: Of preparing for a performance, of a typical performance, what was the hardest part of the Aggie band halftime to prepare for?
I think putting the music with the drill.
In other words, you learn the drill,
And you've got everything.
You count the number of steps in the drill.
Then you count the number of measures in the music.
And you get everything all set for the grand finale.
And then this means that you have to cut some of the music off.
And getting everybody to cut it off at exactly the same time so it will fit the music.
I think that was probably the hardest part.
And like I say, Wednesday was a bad day because it took so many times to go over it until they...

they got it and probably half as many times as it would have taken any other group but even as smart and determined and dedicated as these guys were we still had some trouble with that but after usually after about Thursday or Friday then you see it all fit in together and by Friday and then Saturday morning it was usually they would just something about that audience and

getting the 50 60 000 people whatever we have and getting them all together they just really outdid themselves all right let's make believe that on this hypothetical situation it's a comparatively clear day saturday we've got a home game describe what that day was for you and the band when did things begin and so forth
The typical Saturday day at home would begin for me about 5, 5 30.
I'd have to be up there at 6 30, 6 45 in the morning.
At 6 45 when you get there, all of them will be there except maybe a few seniors who haven't gotten up yet.
They're in section and the drums are over there playing the cadence and they're walking up and down practicing their counter marches.
The drum majors are usually down on the goal line or somewhere, there's some part of the drill that they're just not quite sure about.
They're over there working on that.
At 7 o'clock we take a break and we go through the drill sometime.
If they do it real good, we go through it twice.
at 7.
If it's not real good, we stay sometime until 7.45.
But if it's some of the cross through sometime would give us trouble.
But then usually after we get through with that, well then we depart and we go.
They'll have on their fatigues and they'll go get on their uniforms and we get ready to go.
But now you know they have the march in over there.
That would begin
about two hours before the game started.
I had to be there so I could meet them.
Then we'd have them, we'd have the march in and then we'd have the pregame and then we'd have the game.
So you're talking

say the game started two o'clock you're talking getting up at 5 5 30 in the morning and getting home at 7 6 37 and it's a it's a full day it's a full day for them and uh I don't I thought many times what in the world makes them do this and I think it's uh dedication and pride and and uh
The love for the band and their devotion to each other is the only things that I have come up with as to why they do this.
There were no scholarships.
There were no pay.
No pay involved.
And they do it year after year after year.
And whatever the demand is on their time, well, then they do it.
And I think those things have to enter into it.
I haven't been able to figure out, what in the world are they doing this for?
And that's the reason.
There's just an undying interest in what they're doing and devotion there that I have never seen in another group
Anywhere, not just the bandsmen, but the Aggie band has had a lot of still does, had a lot of fine qualities, and few people really understand this unless they have been in it.
As you think back over the years that you were the director, what were some of the proudest moments in terms of performances?
Were there any that you particularly...
There is one that particularly stands out in my mind.
We went to the Cotton Bowl in 1986, I believe, or 1987, and we played Ohio State University.
Ohio State, without a doubt, has one of the finest bands in this world, marching bands.
And they're all brass, and most of them are music majors, and they really know what, they are just superb.
So I was really looking forward to this, and perhaps
a little apprehensive because we have no music majors, we have no, what you would call, usually the only playing that most of these guys get was in the band.
So we go up there on the morning before the Cotton Bowl performance and we get so many minutes on the field and the Ohio band goes first.

and uh we go up in the stands to watch and I told all the guys in the band to go up and watch them and so they they come they come on the field and they just do an absolutely marvelous job and they they end their drill with coming over to the side and playing climb every mountain and it just it just was so pretty it scared me to death so anyway we went down to the end and
Gathered around, as we always do, and I told him, I said, now, guys, I want to tell you something.
I told you that I would take you anywhere in the United States on any regulation football field, and I would put you up against any band in the world for marching and playing, and you'll do good.
I said, now, this is the time to do a little bit better than you know how to do.
And so we come out there and they just really did beautifully at the rehearsal.
And we had a tune or a march, a kind of a symphonic march that I had arranged for them at the end called Cowbaccade, which is a very dramatic ending.
And we also came to the side like we did quite often.
And they played this thing about as pretty as anything I ever heard.
And so when we got through and we did it again,

I went up in the top and and their band directors were sitting up there as to this day they had done nothing more than say um hello how are you I'm so-and-so I'm so-and-so and this one old kind of short stocky kind of bald-headed guy came over there and he said my name is Mr. is Dr. so-and-so and I didn't know who he was he said I am the retired director of the Ohio State band

and said for years now I've been hearing how fine this band was and said they are better than I thought they were that I heard they were and so you know that that just made my day so for some reason or other the the Aggie band and the Ohio State band seemed to have a lot in common and they were trading spats for epaulettes and they were mixing and talking and
And so that day at that cotton bowl, that's two of the finest bands I have ever seen.
And they were just flawless.
We did a beautiful deal where we spread out for a hundred yards and just a beautiful drill.
And they were, they were, they were, they were fantastic.
And so then when, even when we were leaving on the buses after this was over, when they were still talking and saying goodbye and they were writing each other when we got back in.
So that musically speaking, I think that was probably the,
One of the highlights of my performance, I don't know of anything I ever enjoyed better.
All right, let's go to the other extreme.
Somewhere, something went wrong.
Yeah.
We had one of those.
Well, we had several where they went wrong, but this one deal, we went to Rice, I believe, in maybe 80 or 81.
And Rice is just like going to another planet, really.
They have no earthly desire to see you excel.
They just want to mess you up if they can.
They'd thrown smoke bombs into the band one year and burned a couple of them, burned their boots.
They had that clown running around out there on the field running through them and everything.
But this year it was whistles.
They had probably 150, 200 whistles.
And we had a very difficult, really had a nice drill all worked out.

everything was going real good until we got it all they started blowing these whistles right in the middle of the field and one half of the bugle rank turned five yards too soon and uh they of course by the time then the other half took six steps they were already ten steps apart
And it was one of those deals where we would spread out all over the field and we did what we called a rocket and we had a step one drill where we picked up and then we made the tee.
Well, there was no way in this world they could get back together.
And we had been trying for years things on a football field that I had never seen anybody else try or do.
And I just had wondered, said, these guys are not wind-up people.
They're wind-up machines.
They're people.
They're going to make mistakes.
And I was just wondering when this, hope it didn't, but if it's ever going to happen.
Well, it happened.
And when they came, everything looked pretty good until they came back to Farmington and they couldn't do it.
Because one group was 10 or 15 yards down there and they couldn't stop.
So they just left.
Well, a lot of Aggies thought that, well, this is just terrible.
This is the end of the world.
Of course, you can imagine how I felt and how all the guys in the band felt.

and they made the Houston papers and the coaches were saying oh my goodness the band director was crying well they didn't even see me they don't know what they're talking about but it was a it was bad and they made but they just simply made a mistake a bad one and there's nothing they can do about it so you know humans make mistakes so anyway we went on in the next week I don't remember who we played
But that was probably one of the best drills I've ever seen.
It was step-by-step.
It was absolutely as perfect as you could ever get it.
But a lot of the people just remember that, and they don't remember the good things.
And I don't know of anybody in this world at one time or other that hadn't made a real bad mistake.
So anyway, we did that.
That's about the only time I can ever remember.
But it's something that I'm sure a lot of people, and of course I was reminded of it for,
weeks after that everywhere I went about the blunder.
What about weather?
You must have encountered some astonishing weather conditions somewhere.
We have marched on Kyle Field when it snowed, when there was snow on the field.
We have marched at the halftime whether it's rain, mud, sleet.
or snow and we marched a number of times at the Baylor game at Kyle Field when the Baylor band wouldn't even march.
And they were in the buses and we were out there marching.
We went to Arkansas one time and it was so cold that we couldn't even move the valves on the horns.
Those guys are pretty tough and it didn't really bother them much.
They just did what they had to do.
That was the story of their life.
They did what they had to do and wherever it was

very little griping and fussing and complaining to anybody about anything so it you know it was a it's like a second dedication pride uh and that that that has a lot to do with it did uh the different head football coaches uh express appreciation for the band's efforts we had we had i think marvelous rapport
with the football coaches and the athletic directors and I moved here about the same day or the same week that Emory Ballard and R.C.

Slocum moved here in 1972 and we were really dear friends the coaches kind of adopted me and they took me fishing with them and they took me on all these golf excursions and fundraising things which I dearly loved and then Jackie Sherrill was he was

really really good to us and he came over would eat with us and he came to band hall on several different occasions and wanted to see everything and and then uh of course rc we hunted together honey quail together golf together and uh we were we were very close friends so
I don't know how the relationship could have been any better.
And, of course, with Wally Groff, he was not the athletic director then, but he was in charge of the money.
And, you know, that can get pretty tight sometimes.
And Wally and I don't ever recall having a problem that we couldn't work out.
And so I just was so pleased with our, well, you know, you can brawl it or fry it, but if it were not for those football games,
and the athletic contest.
I doubt very seriously we'd have an Aggie band.
Oh I agree.
And you know you can play all the concerts in the world on all the concert stages and there's nowhere in the world 60-70,000 people gonna see you every Saturday unless you get out there in March.
And I've always felt that way about high school and certainly in college.
The Aggie band makes their reputation on the football field.
So those lines better be straight and that drill better be good because if it's not, that's where you're going to lose it to.
And so it's been a great thing.
Of the other bands in this region of the country,
Which ones do you respect the most?
Well, in the Southwest Conference, I feel that I think my second choice is Texas Tech.
I think they have a wonderful band.
And I think they're...
They not only march well, they play beautifully, and they're usually very cordial to us.
Texas University has a good band, and I appreciate them.
I've always felt like the SMU band was a very true art form band.
No one else did what they did, and no one else did what we did, so you could possibly say that we were the only two originals around.

I feel man for man I think they probably got more sound I don't think it's so much that way anymore but man for man they were just absolutely blow the end out of those things but Texas Tech I've always enjoyed them and I think next to the Aggie band they would probably be my favorite and of course otherwise Ohio State is probably

right up on the list Michigan has a great band and there's so many real real fine ones but you know I really didn't have a whole lot of time to think about how good anybody else was I never ever recall when we're getting set to play somebody that we ever mentioned who we were playing
And I do have heard that down at the Texas band, when Mr. Donino, Dr. Vincent Donino was there, he was a very dear friend of mine, said, well, all year long now, we've just been playing.
Now, this week, we've got a march.
The Aggies are coming.
You got to get those lines straight, and you got to do something.
Now, he told me this.
So, you know, it's just a matter of taste, I think.
Some people probably...
Now, all members of the band were in the Corps.
Right.
Compared to the other Corps members, were there more contracts, more DNC in the band than in the rest of the Corps, or was it just about the same?
Well, I think it's about the same.
We had a lot of folks that were

in the corps just to be in the band and they were not interested in in contracts and were became dnc's but there were a lot of them in the other part of the corps the corps would have a difficult time existing without their dnc's but i think the the the band always had their share of the of the uh of the the uh uh contracts and also we had a very extensive
program for improving our grade system, and our grades were really very high in the band.
I was going to say, compared to the rest of the Corps, weren't band grades higher?
They were higher, especially A Company.
They would get the academic, it seemed like almost every year, they would get the academic flag when they had the award ceremonies.
They would win that almost every year.
How likely was a freshman in the band to be able to march at halftime the first year?
We had a rotation system, and we tried our best, unless they just did not have problems of some kind, that no freshman would miss more than one game.
And we kept up with it every week, and we'd have them over on the side,
And then we tried to fix that.
Now sometime it was, some of them would have to miss more than one, but every week you have people that are hurt, you have people that are sick, and it's necessary to use those alternates in there.
So it was really good to have a large group
And I didn't care how many we had, I didn't want to march for 303, because you could not do, with more than that, it's very difficult to do anything.
It's just really pretty.
That's 300 plus the three drum majors, yeah.
And that's 25 plus 12, I believe, if I remember right.
That's been a long time.
But anyway.
And in terms of their...
military relation you had both Air Force Army and Navy Marines Navy and Marines just like the rest that's right we had all four about were they similar to the Corps in terms of
the percentage that lived on campus compared to the percentage... Well, they had to have special permission to live off campus.
It had to be extenuating circumstances.
Even if they were juniors and seniors?
Even if they were juniors and seniors, they had to live.
They had to live, whether they were married
They had a hardship case, had to live with their grandmother and Brian or something like that.
But they had to live in dorm 9, dorm 11.
That's where we had ours.
And so we, what's so wonderful about that, you can usually find them.
If you don't, they're not in their room, just leave a note and tell them to come in and see you.
And that's, it's one of the most, it's the finest setup for a van I believe I ever saw.
Can you describe, please, the process for selecting drum majors?
We have a committee, and you have one from each class, plus the present drum majors, plus the COs, and I was the head of the committee, and we would have two days of grueling

things for them to do in other words they would have to go inside and direct the national anthem they would have to direct the spirit each one of them then we would have to go outside and they would have to take them through a drill and have to hear their verbal commands and we'll have to see their baton work and then we would go inside and we would go right down the list of

just about everything whether they change their shorts every day or their socks or what they knew it and we would discuss each one about leadership qualities and personal qualities and leadership how meaningful that is to them and whether they're a team player or a hot dog or
And it's quite grueling, and I can only think of one time that I had to break the tie.
And to be honest with you, the band directors would always pick theirs just like anybody else.
And sometimes I wouldn't get any of the top three that they'd pick, and we'd just vote on it, see?
And we'd talk about it and put them on the board, and they usually worked out pretty good.
All three had to be seniors?

have to be seniors then they picked they picked three in an alternate and uh one year we had to use an alternate and we had twin drum majors the twin uh one of the twins made it the other one was the alternate and when this guy left and so we we had we had two you couldn't tell them apart and uh
And let's see, now I think I've heard the term band commander.
Yes, he's appointed by the, we recommend him, I recommend him.
But he's not the drill major.
No, no.
He's the ROTC.
He is the band commander and he's the ROTC.
He's appointed by the commandant.
And they do let me recommend him, and then he's appointed by the commandant.
In terms of prestige...
there was keener competition for which?
To be band commander?

Well, the band commander is supposedly the highest, he's the highest officer in there, but prestige-wise, in my opinion, the drum major's got, they got all the glory, and he got all the work, because they were out there in front, and the head drum major, of course, was the one that does the recall step-off on hullabaloo, and they liked to make a big deal out of that.
One guy cracked a vertebra in his neck one day shaking his head for the
We call him Mooney's, and he cracked a burger right back there.
Had to wear a little old brace, one of the head gun major.
I said, well, see there, if you just go ahead and say it quicker than that, it wouldn't happen to you.
When you arrived, let's talk about the personnel.
When you arrived, were there any minority members of the band, Hispanic?
Yes, we had several of those.
We had several Hispanics and several, we had some people from New York and we didn't have any black folks.
Didn't have any black folks?
No, no.
Any international band members?
We had some from Panama.
Really?
And we would get several of those every year from some country.
I had one from Iroquois maybe?
Do you remember, you said there was no black member of the band when you came?
No.
But after that we had- When do you remember?
Can you describe how that worked?
Well, we had probably, you know, every year we took some if they signed up, but I don't remember when we had the first one.
Do you remember any difficulties, any incidents at all?
No.
Oh, no.
No, we never had any.
One of them, the last year I was there we had a black drum major.
And he was killed about two weeks ago, or about two months ago, a month ago, in a plane crash.

He had applied for a commission and I wrote several letters from him and he got the commission but then they wouldn't let him fly because of some kind of eye problem or something and then he was flying for the Civil Air Patrol and his plane crashed.
See, I believe that this school's record on black-white relations has always been splendid.
Oh, I think it's wonderful.
We never had a menish problem.
I tell people, as an observer, that I have the impression the key thing was not who your parents were, but are you an Aggie or you're not an Aggie?
Absolutely.
It doesn't make any difference about that other.
Not to me, it doesn't.
All right, now let's go to the admission of women in the band.
When did anybody first contact you about?
Well do you remember the Zentgraft deal?
Yes I do.
Do you remember the Zentgraft?
Originally she was challenging the Color Guard and she was challenging the Ross Volunteers as the organization.
She was not in the band.
So she just threw in the ban as an afterthought.
And then she entered that into her deal because we didn't have any.
So did she ever come to talk to you about doing the ban?
No, she never even been in the ban hall.
I wonder if she even was a... She was upset because they wouldn't take her in the color guard, I believe.
And so anyway, then when they went to the judge,
And we were interviewed by, I could see the writing on the wall, just to be perfectly honest with you.
And I told them the first day, I said, hey, we're not gonna win this.
Why don't we just go ahead and do it?
And let us have the $200,000 you're going to spend on this thing, and we'll buy something we really need with it.
Oh, no, no, no, we've got to fight.
Well, anyway, this went on for five years.

And people would, and I said, hey, look, do you think for a minute now in Washington, D.C., they can say, they have such a good band, let's just leave it all male because they'll be the only one then that doesn't have it.
It's not going to work that way.
And then I didn't say anymore.
But anyway, it was quite hush-hush, and I was not allowed to talk about it.
And I said, if you'll just let us do it, we'll do it in no time.
But we had a press conference over there.
There was a representative from every major radio station and TV station in the country, and we took five of them in.
And...
And what year was that?
I'm not real sure.
I think it was
Haskell, I'm not real sure.
It may be in that book over there.
It was in the 80s.
I think it was in the 85 or 80s, somewhere along in there.
And the first one that came in there was a girl about 6'2", and she was an all-state trombone player, and she was an athlete, very nice looking.
And she still writes me.
And she was the first one, she was the only one there, she was the first one to graduate.
Now, within the typical band member, how did they react?
They were all going to quit.
And this presented a problem.
And they came in and said, we're not going to stay, we're going to quit.
I said, now, wait a minute.
So I talked to John, Johnny and I talked about it a lot.
John Colas.
John Colas.
And I said, Johnny, I want to find out one thing from you right quick before we go on here now.
If they all quit like they say they are, which I think we can handle that, are we still going to have a ban?
He said, we will have a ban if they quit.
So I go back to him and I say, now, gentlemen, I want to tell you something.
If you all quit, and boy, I mean they were 100%.
If you quit like you say they are, then the Aggie ban is through.
It's done.
It's finished.
Now, if you want to continue to have the Aggie Band with a few exceptions, you'll stay.
But I have talked to the Vice President of Student Services, and he very confidently told me that they will have a band here
whether you quit or not.
Now, I'm asking you not to quit.
Don't let four or five women ruin this organization.
Said girls have been, said, I don't want girls in this band, but I love girls.
I've been married to one for 42 years.
And they are not going to hurt us like you think they will.
Well, they didn't say anything.
Just looked and stared, glassy.
So they came back, C.O.
came back and said, sir, we're going to try it.
I said, that's fine, because they're going to have a band, and I'm going to stay here, and I can go somewhere else or whatever, but I'm going to stay.
And I think we ought to stay and do it.
And they will wear the same things that you wear.
They will have their hair.
That was the main thing they were concerned about.
They wanted them to look.
